AB  - AI solutions are introduced in various complex, unstructured and perpetually evolving contexts, wherein multiple agents are often needed to cooperate in order to accomplish a given set of objectives. In such environment, flexibility is crucial because such systems are required to alter their operation in accordance with changes occurring in the environment. However, there are problems associated with traditional multi-agent systems to provide the wanted level of flexibility in order to react promptly to the constantly changing environment and handle a variety of sensory inputs. This paper describes a new Dynamic AI Collaboration Framework to address these issues by incorporating multi-modal feedback from vision, audio and text, haptic feedback streams. This framework is composed by a Dynamic Role Assigner based on reinforcement learning that will assign the roles of the agents according to the variations of the environment. This can be done to a much larger extent than in the earlier examples, and flexible adaptive AI agents can alter their roles without any problems according to their assessment of the ongoing task and its environment. This paper also presents an evaluation of the effectiveness of the proposed framework in a number of simulated disaster-response scenarios where our approach proves to be 25% more efficient and 40% more dynamic as compared to the conventional static role allocation based approaches. The findings show that adopting remote multimodal feedback as well as dynamic role allocation strengthen synergistic interactions among AI participants and guarantee optimised performance in critical, transient situations. In this work numerous applications are presented for dynamic AI systems for example in disaster response and industrial automation, in collaborative creative processes and health care showing that dynamic systems have a variety of uses in different fields.
ER  - 

