AB  - As the need for remote medical services continues to expand, there is growing pressure on communication infrastructures to support ultra-reliable, high-speed, and low-latency connectivity. This work examines how Open RAN—a next-generation, software-defined network architecture—can be leveraged to advance remote healthcare delivery in Brazil. Using tele-ultrasound as a critical case study, we performed a series of lab-based evaluations involving real ultrasound hardware integrated within a 5G Open RAN environment. The testbed was established through a collaborative effort with Samsung, Beneficência Portuguesa (a major private healthcare provider in Latin America), and InovaHC, the innovation arm of the region’s largest hospital. The results confirm that Open RAN is capable of sustaining the demanding requirements of remote medical interactions, including live video transmission, tactile feedback, and diagnostic tasks, even when exposed to varying backhaul scenarios. To further guide the development of remote clinical workflows, we propose a classification framework for mobile specialist practice (MSP), identifying critical technical enablers and network capabilities needed to ensure reliable and effective remote examinations.
ER  - 

